article.headline: N.J. starts new streak, wins 15 of 16
article.story: EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Kenyon Martin had 18 points, 15 rebounds and an incredible late block as the New Jersey Nets got back on track after losing for the first time under Lawrence Frank with a 92-86 win over the Miami Heat on Saturday. Richard Jefferson added 25 points and Jason Kidd had four free throws in the final 21.2 seconds to cap a 20-point effort in helping the Nets' rally from a 10-point halftime deficit. The win was the Nets 15th in 16 games overall, and their 14th in 15 games since Frank replaced Byron Scott as coach of the two-time defending Eastern Conference champions in late January. The only loss came Wednesday against Minnesota. Eddie Jones had 21 points to lead Miami, which lost its second straight after winning a season high-tying four games in a row. Caron Butler added 18 points, and Dwayne Wade had 17 for the Heat, who were limited to 38 second-half points. Lamar Odom had 10 points in 17 foul-plagued minutes for Miami, which made only seven field goal in the final quarter. The game was the first of eight scheduled on Saturday, and the inside-out shirt protest by NBA officials over the suspension of referee Michael Henderson for a bad call apparently ended after one day. Officials Dick Bavetta, Tony Brown and Leroy Richardson all wore their shirts the conventional way. They also used their whistles a lot in a game that lasted two hours, 32 minutes and featured 61 personal fouls. Martin and Jefferson combined for 15 of 19 points in a spurt that transformed a 71-67 deficit into an 86-80 lead when Jefferson scored the last of his six straight points with 1:52 to play. A three-point play by Udonis Haslem and two free throws by Bulter cut the lead to 86-85 with 22.1 seconds to play. Kidd hit two free throws after being fouled on the ensuing inbounds play to push the lead to 88-85, and then Martin came up big. Wade, who was guarded by Kidd, drove around top of the key and came down the right side of the lane, putting a floater. Martin came off his man and caught the shot in mid air for a block that could have been considered a steal. Kerry Kittles added two free throws with 13.4 seconds to go and the Heat never had another chance to tie the game. Trailing by 10 at the half, the Nets held Miami to 14 third-quarter points to get within a point entering the fourth quarter. ^Notes:@ Rafer Alston hit two 3-pointers in a row in the first quarter, the first an excuse-me bank shot from the top of the key. ... Nets G Zoran Planinic got his shaggy 60ish-style hair clipped. ...The Nets lead the season series with Miami 2-1. ... New Jersey has won nine straight at home. ... Miami was outscored 34-14 in the paint.
